															</div>
				<div class="info">
					<span class="printuser deleted" data-id="1472934"><img class="small" src="http://www.wikidot.com/common--images/avatars/default/a16.png" alt=""/>(account deleted)</span> <span class="odate time_1398016146 format_%25e%20%25b%20%25Y%2C%20%25H%3A%25M%7Cagohover">20 Apr 2014 17:49</span>
														</div>
			</div>
			<div class="content" id="post-content-2015866">
									

<p>This, and moose's thing. <em>Very much</em> this.</p>
<p>Does anyone remember the red stone disc that sticks to mirrors and allows passage to another world where everything's gotten severely fucky depending on the color an individual person makes the disc turn? <em>That</em> scip's experiment log had a significant creep factor. (And yes, I know others have made this comparison, but it's a no-brainer comparison, really it is.) What disappoints me so much about this test log is that it feels like it could be just as much - possibly even the same basic idea and length and of equal quality, but significantly different enough in details to make it unique - except it feels like the author sort of stopped halfway through and never finished it. There are few things more tragic than a story left only half-told and never finished.</p>
<p>When the (+100-ed) article itself was lackluster but had a link to a test log, I thought to myself &quot;Oh, it's one of those articles where you have to read the test log to understand why it's so freaky.&quot; Then I thought, &quot;Haha, watch the test log be just as lackluster.&quot; I have never been less happy to be right about something, ever. This test log here is a demo, a teaser - a lot of (really good!) buildup to a climax that never comes. There is so much that can and <em>should</em> be done with this, but it cops out just when it's getting really interesting.</p>
<p>If you're trying to make a scip that relies on its test log, but I <em>still</em> have to read the discussion pages to get what's going on even after reading that test log, the article can't really be called complete. Now that I <em>have</em> read the discussion pages and get what's going on…I'm not sure if I'm less annoyed or <em>more</em> annoyed by the lack of substance in the articles. It's real-life level zero, and that's cool. It presents an &quot;edge of the world&quot; for people to fall off of, and that's cool. There are glitchy, presumably hostile entities we can't hunt down roaming around in there, and that's <em>really</em> cool. Imagine if you could get to level zero in a game, and not only is it a glitchy world, but there are new (or I guess, leftover-bit-glitchy) enemies that don't appear in the real game that can appear and kill you but you don't really get to see them and don't know what they do or anything - that would be <em>beyond awesome</em>. And what would gamers do if someone discovered such a thing in a game and went on the internet and told everyone about it? Pretty much what the Foundation ought to do upon discovering the place in real life: Brave all the dangers and face all the fears to try and figure out exactly what the actual hell is going on. They'd race to be the first to get screenshots of the monsters, they'd walk right to the edge to try and figure out exactly where the world ends to the nearest centimeter, they'd have competitions to see who can survive the nighttime in the level the longest or who can survive the most nighttimes, and they'd try to record as much of it to post on the internet as possible to prove their prowess. The Foundation should be doing pretty much the IRL equivalent of that with this thing. It's much easier to Secure, Contain, and Protect a thing the more you understand it, and the Foundation tries to make sense of all the nonsensical things it exists to contain for that very reason.</p>
<p>And why nighttime? And how did the Foundation figure out not to be in there at nighttime? And why won't people talk about what happens at night? That gets into Howell's comments, which I've already thirded, but seriously, so much could be done here!</p>
<p>With over +100 on the log as well as the main article, I feel cheated. I may be only one person, but even as much as I love the idea behind this scip and the test log, and as much as I love to upvote things, I will still withhold my upvote on both pages because they haven't been fully fleshed out. If that isn't worth squat, so be it.</p>

							</div>

								
					
